{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518362"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.07,0.17,0.19,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106662"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5350"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"736"},{"type":"tags","id":"1056"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1944"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42830"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106662"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of gradual onset progressive weakness in his legs, making it difficult for him to walk. He reports concurrent loss of coordination and stiffness in his arms, making it challenging to get dressed. He denies pain, numbness or tingling. He has lost 15 kg in weight. His medical history includes asthma, for which he uses fluticasone/salmeterol as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 60/min and blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg. In his lower limbs, he has fasciculations in his quadriceps bilaterally. He has bilateral leg weakness, left worse than right. He has increased tone with spasticity in the upper limbs bilaterally. He has bilateral arm weakness. His knee jerk and biceps reflexes are hyperreflexic bilaterally; all other reflexes are present in the upper and lower limbs. Light touch, temperature sensation and proprioception are intact in both the upper and lower limbs. Examination of his cranial nerves demonstrates an impaired swallow and tongue fasciculations. He has difficulty rising from a chair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum Na+: 140 mEq/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum K+: 3.7 mEq/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum CK: 100 U/L (30-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENerve conduction studies: normal velocity, normal amplitude, and normal response to repetitive stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following has been shown to slow progression of this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Riluzole","Methotrexate","Interferon-beta","Prednisolone","Vitamin B12 supplementation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation, with progressive weakness, fasciculations, spasticity, hyperreflexia, and signs of bulbar involvement (impaired swallow and tongue fasciculations), is highly suggestive of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), also known as motor neuron disease (MND).\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EALS is characterised by the degeneration of both upper and lower motor neurons. ALS is a diagnosis of exclusion. His normal potassium level, CK level, and nerve conduction studies decrease the likelihood of a neuropathy, neuromuscular junction disorder, or myopathy being the cause of his presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMND involves the degeneration of motor neurons, causing muscles to progressively weaken. ALS is associated with upper and lower limb weakness, causing impaired mobility. Progressive dysphagia can occur with bulbar involvement and results in inadequate caloric intake and weight loss. The hallmark of ALS is the presence of both upper motor neuron signs (spasticity, hyperreflexia) and lower motor neuron signs (flaccid weakness, fasciculations, hyporeflexia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERiluzole\u003C/strong\u003E is a medication specifically indicated for the treatment of ALS. Riluzole works by modulating the release of glutamate, a neurotransmitter that is believed to contribute to motor neuron damage in ALS and thus reduces glutamate excitotoxicity. While riluzole does not cure ALS, multiple clinical trials have shown that it can extend the survival of ALS patients by several months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is an immunosuppressive medication used for various autoimmune conditions and some types of cancer. It is not a standard treatment for ALS and does not have a proven role in slowing down the progression of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon-beta\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used in the treatment of multiple sclerosis, another neurological condition, and is not a standard treatment for ALS. It has not been shown to be effective in slowing down the progression of ALS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a corticosteroid medication that has anti-inflammatory properties. It is used to treat a variety of conditions, but it is not a recommended treatment for ALS. In fact, some studies have suggested that corticosteroids like prednisolone may worsen muscle weakness in ALS patients. As such, prednisolone is not considered an appropriate option for managing ALS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for ALS and has not been shown to significantly impact the progression of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, riluzole is the only medication among the options that has been shown to slow the progression of ALS. It is typically administered orally twice daily. While its effects are modest, it remains an important part of ALS management, alongside supportive care and symptomatic treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Riluzole is administered orally twice daily to slow progression of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), a type of motor neuron disease (MND)..","The neuroprotective effect of Riluzole in treatment of motor neurone disease has been attributed to inhibition of glutamate release.","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is characterized by both upper and lower motor neurological signs."],"references":["Foster LA, Salajegheh MK. Motor Neuron Disease: Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Management. Am J Med. 2019 Jan;132(1):32-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30075105/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-21T15:26:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T15:26:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5350"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106662"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position